Abstract

This study aims to provide insight on the importance of firearms in Valorant, a tactical first-person shooter developed by Riot Games. With economy being a big factor in the strategic aspect of the game, each weapon has unique attributes including fire rate, wall penetration, magazine capacity, and damage to different parts of the body from various distances. The data in this study explores how the different types of weapons influence these various attributes.

Introduction

Valorant was released by Riot Games in 2020 and to this day has made a name for itself as one of the most prominent tactical first-person shooters in recent times. Because I personally have a lot of hours in this game, it is a topic I am quite passionate about and am actually curious to explore. In the context of this Project, I want to go into detail about the specifics of all the different guns in the game. The goal of the game is to reach 13 rounds first, and firearm buyouts can be the turning point in the success of a round. Understanding how weapons function within the games economy is essential for players seeking to optimize performance. The diversity of weapons ranging from pistols and rifles to shotguns and sniper rifles creates multiple layers of decision making during gameplay. Each guns unique attributes influence their effectiveness in various situations, and decisions on whether to save or invest in weapons during a round can determine the outcome of a match. The objective of this study is to compare how different weapon types dictate their price point, as well as how worth it a gun is in relate to its damage dealt at different distances.

loadout

Data

The dataset I decided to use was found on kaggle (Valorant Weapon Stats Kaggle.com). This csv file contained information about 17 of the unique guns found in Valorant with information regarding their weapon type, price, fire rate, wall penetration, magazine capacity, as well as head damage, body damage, and leg damage from close, medium, and far range. The inclusion criteria is the details found from hovering the stats of each gun, not including run speed, equip speed, 1st shot accuracy, and reload speed which arent as important in the context of this study. A current limitation is that this dataset does not contain information about the newest gun, the outlaw which was recently released. I also referenced data found in Valorant Weapon Stats Analysis Kaggle.com for my analysis.

Analysis and Results

There are a total of 17 guns in the game, with 6 different weapon types. There are 5 sidearms, 2 submachine guns, 4 rifles, 2 snipers, 2 shotguns, and 2 heavy/machine guns.

The average price of each type of gun is listed below.

average_price <- tapply(val$Price, val$Weapon_Type, mean)

print(average_price)
##   Heavy   Rifle Shotgun Sidearm     SMG  Sniper 
##    2400    2600    1200     380    1300    2800

This is a barplot used to showcase the average price as well as the mean line

bar_positions <- barplot(average_price,

Damage Dropoff

Now I want to represent how damage dropoff differs depending on the gun type. When a bullet hits head, body, and leg level respectively, there is a difference in the amount of damage dealt. Also when hit at a different range, there is potential for a range damage dropoff.

This is representative of the average damage dealt at a close range

avg_head_close <- tapply(val$HDMG_0, val$Weapon_Type, mean)
avg_body_close <- tapply(val$BDMG_0, val$Weapon_Type, mean)
avg_leg_close <- tapply(val$LDMG_0, val$Weapon_Type, mean)

print(avg_head_close)
##   Heavy   Rifle Shotgun Sidearm     SMG  Sniper 
##   83.50  155.75   44.50   91.40   72.50  228.50
print(avg_body_close)
##   Heavy   Rifle Shotgun Sidearm     SMG  Sniper 
##    34.0    44.5    19.5    30.4    26.5   125.5
print(avg_leg_close)
##   Heavy   Rifle Shotgun Sidearm     SMG  Sniper 
##   28.50   36.25   16.50   25.40   22.50  106.00

This is representative of the average damage dealt at a long range

avg_head_long <- tapply(val$HDMG_2, val$Weapon_Type, mean)
avg_body_long <- tapply(val$BDMG_2, val$Weapon_Type, mean)
avg_leg_long <- tapply(val$LDMG_2, val$Weapon_Type, mean)

print(avg_head_long)
##   Heavy   Rifle Shotgun Sidearm     SMG  Sniper 
##   72.00  147.75   19.00   74.20   64.00  228.50
print(avg_body_long)
##   Heavy   Rifle Shotgun Sidearm     SMG  Sniper 
##    29.5    42.5     9.5    24.2    23.5   125.5
print(avg_leg_long)
##   Heavy   Rifle Shotgun Sidearm     SMG  Sniper 
##    24.5    34.5     8.5    20.2    19.5   106.0

Barplot of Damage Outputs

damage_matrix <- rbind(
  Head_Close = avg_head_close,
  Body_Close = avg_body_close,
  Leg_Close = avg_leg_close,
  Head_Long = avg_head_long,
  Body_Long = avg_body_long,
  Leg_Long = avg_leg_long
)

print(damage_matrix)
##            Heavy  Rifle Shotgun Sidearm  SMG Sniper
## Head_Close  83.5 155.75    44.5    91.4 72.5  228.5
## Body_Close  34.0  44.50    19.5    30.4 26.5  125.5
## Leg_Close   28.5  36.25    16.5    25.4 22.5  106.0
## Head_Long   72.0 147.75    19.0    74.2 64.0  228.5
## Body_Long   29.5  42.50     9.5    24.2 23.5  125.5
## Leg_Long    24.5  34.50     8.5    20.2 19.5  106.0

bar_colors <- c("red", "purple", "yellow", "orange", "blue", "green")

bar_positions <- barplot(damage_matrix,
                         beside = TRUE,  
                         col = bar_colors,
                         main = "Average Damage Comparison",
                         xlab = "Weapon Type",
                         ylab = "Average Damage",
                         ylim = c(0, max(damage_matrix) + 50),
                         las = 1)

weapon_types <- rownames(val$Weapon_Type)
axis(1, at = bar_positions[0, ], labels = weapon_types, las = 2)  

legend("topleft", legend = c("Head Close", "Body Close", "Leg Close", "Head Long", "Body Long", "Leg Long"), 
       fill = bar_colors, 
       title = "Damage Type")

From this data we can tell that there is a clear difference in the damage output of a headshot vs any other shot on the body. The average headshot damage at close range is 112.6916667, while the average body shot damage is 46.7333333, and the leg shot damage is 39.1916667. Similarly, at long range, the average headshot damage is 100.9083333, compared to body shots at 42.45 and leg shots at 35.5333333.

However there is not much distinction when comparing the damage dropoff at a larger distance. While there is indeed a difference, it is not as extreme.

Conclusion

So the goal of this Project was to compare the different price points of the different weapon types and test damage done at different parts of the body at long and short range. In order to do this, I had to code for finding the average price of each gun type, including Sidearm, SMG, Rifle, Sniper, Shotgun, Heavy. I also graphed this in the barplot @ref(fig:price). In order to discuss damage dropoff, I frst had to find the average of a headshot, body shot, and leg shot at close range as well as long range. This was compiled into a matrix before being graphed into a barplot as well at @ref(fig:dmg).From the results we can easily tell that hitting a headshot is ideal in Valorant because it does much more damage than hitting any other part of the body. We can also see that different weapons types will affect how much damage it does in comparison to each other, with the sniper doing the most damage in general. This data gives a lot of insight on what guns are the most beneficial to use.
